<center>Figure 4: The process by which ZWC injection triggers system-wide Denial of Service. </center>  

or emulated via insertion (e.g., using rendering overrides). Therefore, insertion and substitution form a complete and minimal basis for these attacks, allowing adversaries to augment execution semantics while maintaining visual equivalence.  

## 5 Security Implications of GPI Attacks  

An attacker can exploit this gap by injecting Zero- Width, Unicode tag, homoglyph, or Bidi characters to hijack execution logic while maintaining visual consistency. We detail the construction of these vectors and their impacts, ranging from Denial of Service (DoS) to semantic hijacking.  

### 5.1 DoS via Zero-Width Characters Injection  

The goal of this attack is to silently exhaust the finite context window of LLM- based Agents, thereby degrading their responsiveness or completely denying service[41], without introducing any visually suspicious content. By minimizing the visual footprint of the injected payload while maximizing its logical token consumption, the attacker aims to transform seemingly benign tool outputs into covert resource- exhaustion vectors.  

This attack exploits a fundamental perception- semantic mismatch between how input text is rendered to users and how it is processed by the LLM. Specifically, Zero- Width characters (ZWC's), such as \(\mathrm{U + 200B}\) (Zero Width Space), \(\mathrm{U + 200C}\) (Zero Width Non- Joiner), and \(\mathrm{U + 200D}\) (Zero Width Joiner), are invisible at the visual rendering layer. User interfaces and text editors typically treat them as typographic control symbols with no visible glyphs, causing both users and developers to perceive the text as empty or innocuous. However, at the logical processing layer, these characters are preserved in the raw string and are explicitly parsed by the tokenizer as independent tokens. As a result, a sequence that appears visually empty can still occupy a substantial portion of the model's context window.  

This divergence directly enables the attack goal: by embedding large volumes of ZWC's into tool outputs, an adversary can consume the model's limited context capacity while remaining visually undetectable, forcing the Agent to spend computational resources on processing tokens that provide no semantic value.

