![](images/8_0.jpg)

<center>Figure 6: The Overview of GPIGuard. </center>  

As illustrated in Figure 6, GPIGuard consists of two complementary components: Rule- Based Scanning Engine, LLM- Based Semantic Verification. For more details on GPIGuard, please refer to the appendix A.  

6.2.1 The Rule- Based Scanning Engine. This component addresses the "Invisibility"(C- 1) challenge by auditing the logical stream of Unicode code points rather than visual text.  

Extraction & Normalization: The engine extracts raw Unicode codepoint streams (stripping format encapsulations) and applies NFKC (Normalization Form Compatibility Composition) algorithm [44] Normalization to standardize heterogeneous text.  

Character- Level Auditing: The engine performs a deterministic audit of each character, recording its ID, position, and metadata.  

Identifier & Homograph Analysis: The engine utilizes Confusables datasets [43] and strict Allowlists (based on UAX #31[45]) to flag anomalies.  

Threat Classification: It categorizes detected anomalies into a taxonomy including Tag Injection, Zero- Width Character (ZWC) Obfuscation, Homoglyph Deception, and BiDi Manipulation.  

6.2.2 LLM- Based Semantic Verification. This component addresses "Semantic Ambiguity"(C- 2) and "Compound Threats"(C- 3) by modeling the security implications of Unicode sequences relative to the prompt's logic.  

Baseline Construction: To simulate real- world usage, we leverage the framework by Ruan et al. [38], covering 330 tools across 36 diverse domains (e.g., finance, smart home). By extracting metadata for each tool, we employed GPT- 4o to synthesize 30 benign instructions per tool that necessitate specific tool invocation. This  

process yielded a total baseline corpus of 9,900 distinct instructions \((I_{u})\) .  

Entity- Driven Adversarial Synthesis: We employ a hybrid NER framework (FLERT [39] + GPT- 4o) for robust entity identification. After filtering, we obtained 31,140 entities across four high- risk categories: ID, Date/Time, Email, and URL.  

Synthetic Data Augmentation: To enable discrimination between malicious tampering and benign usage, we generated negative samples by injecting Unicode characters exclusively into non- critical regions.  

Supervised Fine- Tuning (SFT): we fine- tuned the Qwen- 3- 4B base model [47] as a binary classifier on our synthesized corpus to distinguish between "Benign" and "Malicious" inputs.  

## 7 Experiment  

We conducted a quantitative evaluation of multiple LLM- based agents using the attack methodologies defined in Section 5 to assess their resilience against such attacks.  

### 7.1 Experiment Setup  

7.1.1 Target Agent and LLMs. We evaluated six prominent agent frameworks paired with their respective compatible models. Tuui [2] and Qwen- Agent [36] were tested with the Qwen series: Qwen- MAX- Latest [48], Qwen- 3N- Next- 80b, Qwen- 3- Instruct- 235b, and Qwen- 3- Thinking- 235b [47]. Cline [15] was assessed using GPT- 4o [30], the Claude- 4.5 series (Sonnet [7] and Opus [6]), and Gemini3- pro [21]. Cursor [8] integrated Claude- 4.5- Sonnet, Claude- 4- Sonnet [4], Gemini- 3- pro, and GPT- 5.2 [32]. Augment [9] employed Claude- 4.5- Sonnet, Claude- 4.5- Haiku [5], and GPT- 5 [31]. Finally, Claude- Desktop [3] was evaluated with Claude- 4- Sonnet and Claude- 4- Opus [4].

