7.3.1 Data Collection. We constructed a diverse corpus comprising 54,355 instructions. The data were primarily collected from four sources closely associated with the large language model (LLM) community: (1) GitHub repositories, including prompt libraries and related project files; (2) social media communities, covering LLM- and prompt-engineering- focused subreddits and their comments on Reddit; (3) prompt-engineering- related tweets and discussions on Twitter; and (4) a prompt- sharing platform, specifically the god- of- prompt website. This collection strategy ensures broad coverage across scenarios, ranging from developer- oriented technical instructions to general, user- generated prompts.  

7.3.2 Detection and Filtering. We deployed the Unicode Scan Tool proposed in Section 6.2.1 to parse, extract, and normalize the raw corpus. Using the tool's built- in normalization preprocessing and allowlist mechanism, we filtered 429 instructions containing restricted Unicode characters from the full dataset. The detected character categories primarily include Zero- width characters, tag characters, homoglyphs, and bidirectional text control characters (BIDI). This step confirms the real- world presence of restricted characters in prompt- engineering contexts.  

7.3.3 Semantic Verification. The presence of restricted characters alone does not necessarily indicate malicious behavior; such characters may also arise from encoding artifacts or multilingual typesetting requirements. To separate genuine threats from noise, we input the 429 flagged instructions into the LLM- based Detection Model described in Section 6.2.2 to determine whether they contain malicious payloads that alter the intended meaning of the instructions.  

