## 8 Related Work  

### 8.1 Evolution of Prompt Injection Attacks  

In the realm of prompt injection attacks, early methods focused on generating adversarial suffixes to manipulate model responses. For instance, Zou et al.[50] introduced the Greedy Coordinate Gradient (GCG) method, an automated attack strategy that combines gradient search with greedy heuristics. This approach optimizes universal adversarial suffixes—often manifesting as nonsensical garbled text or random symbols—to induce affirmative responses from models to harmful instructions. However, the adversarial suffixes generated by GCG lack stealthiness and are easily identifiable by

<--- Page Split --->

human observers[24]. To address this, Chao et al.[14] proposed the Prompt Automatic Iterative Refinement (PAIR) framework. Unlike the token- level optimization of GCG, PAIR employs a prompt- level attack strategy, generating adversarial suffixes that are semantically coherent and human- readable. Nevertheless, the malicious intent within these prompts remains fully exposed to human scrutiny.  

### 8.2 Unicode-Based Imperceptible Attacks  

Building on the need for greater imperceptibility, researchers have explored Unicode- based techniques to create visually deceptive attacks. Boucher et al.[12] leveraged the characteristics of Unicode encoding to propose a class of imperceptible text adversarial attacks. Their work demonstrated that without altering the visual reading experience for humans, such perturbations can significantly degrade the performance of various natural language processing tasks, including machine translation and text classification, and can even precipitate denial- of- service attacks. Extending this line of research, Cooper et al.[17] constructed the first hate speech dataset containing real- world homoglyph perturbations, further revealing the vulnerability of existing Transformer models to such visual deception attacks. They argued that due to the continuous expansion of the Unicode homoglyph repository, traditional defense mechanisms relying on static mapping tables are insufficient to counter dynamically evolving obfuscation attacks. As a solution, Cooper et al. proposed a novel paradigm utilizing LLMs [16] to detect and normalize potential homoglyphs within hate speech, thereby enhancing model robustness.  

### 8.3 Existing Mitigation Tools  

Despite these advancements, existing tools and standards for mitigating such attacks often fall short in handling visual spoofing effectively. Transliteration utilities like Unicodec [35] prioritize phonetic approximation over visual representation, rendering them unable to detect visual spoofing. Similarly, script- specific libraries such as cyrtranslit [34] exhibit limited scope, handling only Cyrillic- Latin mappings and lacking the generalizability to address mixed- script attacks. While Unicode normalization standards (e.g., NFC/NFKC) [44] offer basic data sanitization, they overlook the semantic context of characters. A pertinent example is the Cyrillic 'a': valid in Russian syntax, it poses a severe security risk as a potential homograph attack when embedded in Latin- based URLs.  

## 9 Limitation  

In this section, we discuss the limitations of our current prototype and potential improvements.  

Generalization to Low- Resource Languages. Our evaluation prioritized mainstream languages and standard tool scenarios. While the scanning engine is script- agnostic, the semantic verification model's robustness in low- resource languages or specialized domains remains to be fully validated, warranting broader corpus diversity in future work.  

Evolving Unicode Standards. Our detection relies on current specifications (e.g., UAX #31). As the Unicode standard evolves,  

static allworlds require periodic updates to ensure continued coverage against emerging vectors exploiting newly introduced character properties.  

## 10 Conclusion  

In this paper, we uncover the "Perception- Semantic Gap" in tool- integrated LLM agents, demonstrating how Ghost Prompt Injection (GPI) exploits visual- logical discrepancies to execute invisible Denial of Service (DoS) and logic hijacking attacks. Furthermore, to detect these widespread vulnerabilities, we propose GPIGuard, a hybrid framework that combines codepoint auditing with semantic verification. Validated on real- world data, GPIGuard effectively filters benign encoding noise while neutralizing malicious payloads, which establishes a critical defense baseline for securing the logical integrity of autonomous agent instructions against imperceptible threats.

